tool.name: RadialLineOfSight

param.name: Input_Observer_Features
param.dialogReference:
Point features of observer locations. Visibility modifiers are:

  • SPOT: absolute elevation of the location. If SPOT is set for one observer it must be set for ALL observers, otherwise the field will be ignored.

  • OFFSETA: observer height above the surface.

  • OFFSETB: terrain offset above the surface.

  • AZIMUTH1: left angle in the horizontal field of view.

  • AZIMUTH2: right angle in the horizontal field of view.

  • RADIUS1: Nearest distance to consider in the visiblity.

  • RADIUS2: Farthest distance to consider in the visibility.

  • VERT1: top angle in the vertical field of view.

  • VERT2: bottom angle in the vertical field of view.
param.pythonReference: There is no python reference for this parameter.

param.name: Observer_Height_Above_Surface
param.dialogReference: Additional height added above the surface at each observer location from Input Observer Features. Default is 2. If the input Observer has a value for the OFFSET A field, that value is used instead.
param.pythonReference: There is no python reference for this parameter.

param.name: Radius_Of_Observer
param.dialogReference: Radius distance from observer locations to consider for visibility. If the input Observer has a value for the RADIUS2 field, that value is used instead.
param.pythonReference: There is no python reference for this parameter.

param.name: Input_Surface
param.dialogReference: Input raster surface. You must select an elevation raster layer.
param.pythonReference: There is no python reference for this parameter.

param.name: Output_Visibility
param.dialogReference: Output polygon features denoting visible (green) and non-visible (red) areas.
param.pythonReference: There is no python reference for this parameter.

param.name: Force_Visibility_To_Infinity__Edge_Of_Surface_
param.displayname: Force Visibility To Infinity (Edge Of Surface)
param.dialogReference:
If the visibility analysis is to go to the edge of the surface.

  • Unchecked - Visibitliy will be contained to the maximum RADIUS2 distance. This is the default.

  • Checked - Visibility will go to the edge of the input surface.
param.pythonReference: There is no python reference for this parameter.

param.name: Spatial_Reference
param.pythonReference: There is no python reference for this parameter.

tool.summary: Shows the areas visible (green) and not visible (red) to an observer at a specified distance and viewing angle.
tool.usage:
• This tool requires Spatial Analyst.

  • This tool uses Viewshed to calculate visibility.

  • Intermediate datasets are projected to a localized Azimuthal Equidistant projection to maintain fidelity of distance and direction.

  • Output area polygons have a visibility field showing the number of observers that can view a given area.

  • For more detailed information on the visibility modifiers use in the Observers parameter read the Controlling the Visibility Analysis topic in Using Viewshed and Observer Points for Visibility Analysis.

  • This tool will use earth curvature and refractivity calculations if the Input Surface will support it.

  • Units of the heights are the units of the elevation surface; distance units are in the linear units of the coordinate system of the features class; angular measurements are in degrees.

  • Use Add Radial Line of Sight Observer Fields first, to force all input control parameters for observers.
